      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction, a fascinating chemical dance, is essentially the browning of bread crusts, which is a complex cascade of reactions involving amino acids and reducing sugars. It's not just one thing, but a chain reaction that produces hundreds of different flavor and aroma compounds. You'll see this happen when the heat gets high enough, typically starting around 285°F (140°C) and really kicking into high gear as it approaches 300°F (150°C) and beyond. Think of it like a massive, uncontrolled, yet delicious, browning frenzy in the oven!",
