    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that's cool. u kept saying it's messy and a \"chaotic symphony\" though. is it basically just random stuff happening in the oven, or is there a way to control it so the crust doesn't just end up burnt or tasting weird?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While the reaction *feels* chaotic, much like a poorly organized band practice, there are definitely ways to steer the process away from a burnt, acrid mess! You can control it by managing the variables, which is key to good baking.\n\nThe primary levers you pull are temperature, time, and moisture. If you let the temperature climb too high too fast, you skip the nuanced flavor development and jump straight to pyrolysis—that's when things burn, which is like a very angry, smoky, burnt-out section of the kitchen. To control it, you want a steady, moderate heat that allows the initial reactions to proceed slowly enough to build complexity, rather than just flash-browning. This is why bakers often use steam initially and then let the heat dry out the surface for the final color.",
      "source": "target",
